restrictions on place,
where you can go,

00:33:56.250 --> 00:33:59.940
or maybe people telling you
something you may not believe is

00:33:59.940 --> 00:34:04.070
true, or restrictions on access to
places you just can't go in Cuba.

00:34:04.070 --> 00:34:06.970
How do you get to a point,
which sounds like you have,

00:34:06.970 --> 00:34:09.490
where you know what
you're talking about

00:34:09.490 --> 00:34:13.510
and you really believe what you've
seen and heard you can confirm it,

00:34:13.510 --> 00:34:15.170
you're comfortable with it?

00:34:15.170 --> 00:34:18.060
&gt;&gt; Mark Kurlansky: Well,
language is kind of essential.

00:34:18.060 --> 00:34:20.810
I've been speaking
Spanish since I was a kid.

00:34:20.810 --> 00:34:27.390
I originally learned
from Puerto Ricans.

00:34:27.390 --> 00:34:29.450
And you know, some
things you can't --

00:34:29.450 --> 00:34:32.440
you have to operate differently
in different countries.

00:34:32.440 --> 00:34:35.830
Cuba isn't a country where you
can get everything confirmed

00:34:35.830 --> 00:34:37.130
by the Cuban government.

00:34:37.130 --> 00:34:42.640
It's also a country where you can't
work without the Cuban government.

00:34:42.640 --> 00:34:45.160
They get very uneasy if
you're talking to people

00:34:45.160 --> 00:34:47.630
without them knowing about it.

00:34:47.630 --> 00:34:50.060
Baseball in particular, you
know, this one of these things

00:34:50.060 --> 00:34:51.640
where you wouldn't think about it,

00:34:51.640 --> 00:34:54.850
but talking to baseball
players makes them very nervous

00:34:54.850 --> 00:34:58.180
because there's major-league
scouts that are going around trying

00:34:58.180 --> 00:35:00.040
to talk these guys into defecting.

00:35:00.040 --> 00:35:02.440 position:56%
So, you know, who's this guy really?

00:35:02.440 --> 00:35:09.470
You just have to learn to
work with these difficulties.

00:35:09.470 --> 00:35:11.270
I mean, it's a little
difficult in Cuba.

00:35:11.270 --> 00:35:13.180
Listen, it's more difficult
in Mexico

00:35:13.180 --> 00:35:18.440
because the Mexican government is
just really difficult to work with.

00:35:18.440 --> 00:35:22.490 position:56%
It's just part of the game you play.

00:35:22.490 --> 00:35:24.760
You learn how to play it.

00:35:24.760 --> 00:35:30.800
It's sometimes frustrating.

00:35:30.800 --> 00:35:34.630
Yeah, there are places you
can't go, though not too many.

00:35:34.630 --> 00:35:38.260 position:56%
Not too many, and most of the places
you can't go aren't places I'm

00:35:38.260 --> 00:35:42.350
particularly interested in
anyway, because I really don't care

00:35:42.350 --> 00:35:45.050
that much about military bases.

00:35:45.050 --> 00:35:48.070
So you just learn to deal with it.

00:35:48.070 --> 00:35:49.370
Yeah?

00:35:49.370 --> 00:35:51.450
&gt;&gt; I have a question for you.

00:35:51.450 --> 00:35:56.180
You might be the guy who has a one
word title, but you're also a guy

00:35:56.180 --> 00:36:03.320
who really tends to focus on these
grand global transnational sort

00:36:03.320 --> 00:36:04.620
of stories.

00:36:04.620 --> 00:36:09.200
So I was curious how
it felt to change that

00:36:09.200 --> 00:36:15.500
and to really limit your scope a
little bit, and also how you feel

00:36:15.500 --> 00:36:18.420
like your background as more

00:36:18.420 --> 00:36:22.310
of a global transnational
historian has helped you

00:36:22.310 --> 00:36:26.050
in limiting that scope to Havana?

00:36:26.050 --> 00:36:29.030
&gt;&gt; Mark Kurlansky:
Well, it felt great.

00:36:29.030 --> 00:36:34.430
All my books aren't
on global things.

00:36:34.430 --> 00:36:38.050
I've done other books that were,
you know, very narrowly focused,

00:36:38.050 --> 00:36:41.050
and I've done fiction
books on particular places.

00:36:41.050 --> 00:36:46.690
I've done all kinds of
things, but I enjoyed very much

00:36:46.690 --> 00:36:49.900
when this was proposed to me, the
idea of just focusing on Havana.

00:36:49.900 --> 00:36:51.920
I mean, I didn't even
want to do Cuba.

00:36:51.920 --> 00:36:53.780
I just wanted to do Havana.

00:36:53.780 --> 00:36:58.800
That was something that I enjoyed.

00:36:58.800 --> 00:37:01.230
I supposed it took some discipline

00:37:01.230 --> 00:37:04.190 position:56%
because the reason I do these global
books is I kind of think like that

00:37:04.190 --> 00:37:05.990 position:56%
and everything just keeps expanding.

00:37:05.990 --> 00:37:08.880
Fortunately, this was
a fairly short book

00:37:08.880 --> 00:37:12.300
so I could stop it before
it got out to the world,

00:37:12.300 --> 00:37:15.150
and just keep it focused on Havana.

00:37:15.150 --> 00:37:16.450
Yeah?

00:37:16.450 --> 00:37:19.550
&gt;&gt; Can I ask you about
a different book?

00:37:19.550 --> 00:37:20.850
&gt;&gt; Mark Kurlansky: Okay.

00:37:20.850 --> 00:37:23.150
&gt;&gt; Since we are at a
Library of Congress event,

00:37:23.150 --> 00:37:28.070
I wonder if you could talk about
how you got the idea for "Food

00:37:28.070 --> 00:37:31.550
of a Younger Land" and what it
was like to work with the LOC

00:37:31.550 --> 00:37:34.730
to have access to those records?

00:37:34.730 --> 00:37:36.760
&gt;&gt; Mark Kurlansky: Well, this
would be the place to ask me that.

00:37:36.760 --> 00:37:40.810
Yeah, "Food of the Younger Land"
was a book that I did entirely

00:37:40.810 --> 00:37:42.150
in the Library of Congress

00:37:42.150 --> 00:37:47.880
from an archive there
of WPA writings on food.

00:37:47.880 --> 00:37:53.550
It was a very pleasant experience
to just go to the Library

00:37:53.550 --> 00:37:59.810
of Congress every day and put on
my little gloves, get these files

00:37:59.810 --> 00:38:04.630
and look through these old onion
skin carbon copies of stuff

00:38:04.630 --> 00:38:10.640
that people had written
in the 1930s.

00:38:10.640 --> 00:38:12.880
I just tremendously enjoyed it.

00:38:12.880 --> 00:38:14.240
I mean, the Library of Congress --

00:38:14.240 --> 00:38:18.500
I'm not saying this because
we're here, but we are here --

00:38:18.500 --> 00:38:20.110
is a great place to work.

00:38:20.110 --> 00:38:24.190
They are all set up for people like
me who want to do things like that.

00:38:24.190 --> 00:38:25.490
&gt;&gt; A question over here.

00:38:25.490 --> 00:38:28.440
First of all, thank you so much.

00:38:28.440 --> 00:38:32.100
I was just in Havana in June and it
has filled in a lot of gaps for me.

00:38:32.100 --> 00:38:35.740
I'm curious how you have seen the
hopes of the Cuban people change

00:38:35.740 --> 00:38:37.660
over the decades that
you've been there?

00:38:37.660 --> 00:38:39.880
The hopes of the people,
so the hopes

00:38:39.880 --> 00:38:41.930
and dreams of the Cuban people.

00:38:41.930 --> 00:38:43.230
&gt;&gt; Mark Kurlansky: The hopes --

00:38:43.230 --> 00:38:44.920
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:38:44.920 --> 00:38:50.610
&gt;&gt; Mark Kurlansky: Well, you know,
at the time of the revolution,

00:38:50.610 --> 00:38:55.790
young people, and not
just young people,

00:38:55.790 --> 00:39:00.270
people were very excited
about the revolution.

00:39:00.270 --> 00:39:04.060
Getting rid of their -- it was
almost like trying to get rid

00:39:04.060 --> 00:39:08.080
of their entire history, pushing
out all of the Spanish stuff

00:39:08.080 --> 00:39:11.370
and the slave stuff and
all the burdens of history

00:39:11.370 --> 00:39:13.660
and creating this new society.

00:39:13.660 --> 00:39:15.270
It felt very exciting, you know.

00:39:15.270 --> 00:39:18.010
As I said, it felt like
this experimental society

00:39:18.010 --> 00:39:21.420
where you would try
all of these things.

00:39:21.420 --> 00:39:23.210
But it was based on a bargain.

00:39:23.210 --> 00:39:28.300
The bargain was, the Cuban
government said you're not going

00:39:28.300 --> 00:39:29.760
to get rich.

00:39:29.760 --> 00:39:33.300
You are to abandon
materialism and just contribute

00:39:33.300 --> 00:39:35.760
to your society in any way you can.

00:39:35.760 --> 00:39:37.970
And in exchange for that,
we will look after you.

00:39:37.970 --> 00:39:39.270
We'll give you your housing.

00:39:39.270 --> 00:39:40.570
We'll give you your food.

00:39:40.570 --> 00:39:41.870
We'll give you your education.

00:39:41.870 --> 00:39:44.220
We'll give you your healthcare.

00:39:44.220 --> 00:39:46.790
And that worked reasonably well

00:39:46.790 --> 00:39:48.760
until the collapse
of the Soviet Union.

00:39:48.760 --> 00:39:52.210
Then suddenly, there
wasn't enough money.

00:39:52.210 --> 00:39:56.800
What the government was providing
wasn't enough for people.

00:39:56.800 --> 00:39:59.750
The government started allowing
people to do other things,

00:39:59.750 --> 00:40:01.970
like open their own restaurants.

00:40:01.970 --> 00:40:06.870
And as soon as you open that window
of capitalism of making money

00:40:06.870 --> 00:40:10.580
for yourself, suddenly you know,
like doctors are complaining

00:40:10.580 --> 00:40:12.230
that they aren't getting
paid enough.

00:40:12.230 --> 00:40:13.840
They never used to
complain about that.

00:40:13.840 --> 00:40:15.510
The government made them doctors

00:40:15.510 --> 00:40:17.790
and this was their
social responsibility.

00:40:17.790 --> 00:40:19.480
That whole thing kind
of fell apart as soon

00:40:19.480 --> 00:40:21.970
as you opened this
window of capitalism.

00:40:26.690 --> 00:40:27.990
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:40:27.990 --> 00:40:29.290
This is really amazing.

00:40:29.290 --> 00:40:30.730
I'm looking forward
to reading your book,

00:40:30.730 --> 00:40:32.100
having read some of your others.

00:40:32.100 --> 00:40:34.580
I had a chance to live in the
Caribbean for quite a while.

00:40:34.580 --> 00:40:37.670
And while I was there, got
introduced to the music style

00:40:37.670 --> 00:40:41.220
of the Nueva Trova, which was
very popular after the revolution,

00:40:41.220 --> 00:40:44.120
and Silvio Rodriguez and people
like that talking about places

00:40:44.120 --> 00:40:49.390
like Playa Giron and really
emphasizing the cultural identity

00:40:49.390 --> 00:40:50.690
of the people.

00:40:50.690 --> 00:40:57.950
And I was just curious
to know how evoking

00:40:57.950 --> 00:41:01.440
that passion has really moved
forward in terms of the importance

00:41:01.440 --> 00:41:04.780
of that style of music, that
style of culture in modern Cuba,

00:41:04.780 --> 00:41:07.980 position:56%
especially in light of the political
changes that are occurring.

00:41:07.980 --> 00:41:09.280
&gt;&gt; Mark Kurlansky: Yeah.

00:41:09.280 --> 00:41:10.580
Well, it's still very much around.

00:41:10.580 --> 00:41:13.790
And those concerts are still
tremendously popular and,

00:41:13.790 --> 00:41:18.200
by the way, cost almost
nothing to go to.

00:41:18.200 --> 00:41:22.140
It remains a strong tradition and
a lot of those singers from back

00:41:22.140 --> 00:41:25.700
in the 60s are still singing.

00:41:25.700 --> 00:41:32.100
Also [inaudible] and
all sorts of things.

00:41:32.100 --> 00:41:35.890
Cuba doesn't seem to
lose music forms.

00:41:35.890 --> 00:41:37.980
It just keeps adding to them.

00:41:37.980 --> 00:41:45.410
I'm facing this sign that says
"Wrap it up" in large red letters.

00:41:45.410 --> 00:41:49.550
So I'm sorry I can't -- Well,
do you have a quick question?

00:41:49.550 --> 00:41:52.280
&gt;&gt; I was going to say, since
you were a food writer,

00:41:52.280 --> 00:41:57.360
I'd like to hear something
about the food of Havana.

00:41:57.360 --> 00:42:00.810
&gt;&gt; Mark Kurlansky:
That's a quick question?

00:42:00.810 --> 00:42:06.700
Well, you know, food in
Cuba is Cuban history,

00:42:06.700 --> 00:42:09.470
so it's a little bit Spanish
and it's a little bit African

00:42:09.470 --> 00:42:13.190
and sometimes it's a
little bit of Indian in it.

00:42:13.190 --> 00:42:16.510
And there's a bunch
of American in it.

00:42:16.510 --> 00:42:23.480 position:56%
It's a mixture of all those cultures
that have passed through Havana.

00:42:23.480 --> 00:42:24.780
I think that's it.

00:42:24.780 --> 00:42:26.580
Thank you.

